Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to NFTs
NFTs are cryptographic assets on a blockchain. As the name suggests, non-fungible means the assets are unique and have unique identification codes and metadata that distinguish them from each other. Examples of NFTs include digital art, in-game items and digital certificates. 
NFTs, unlike fungible tokens, are unique cryptographic tokens that exist on a blockchain and cannot be replicated and thus, every token is unique. Due to the immutable nature of blockchain transactions, once an NFT is minted onto the blockchain, data cannot be altered. Thus, with NFTs, we can prove the ownership of an NFT by looking into the transaction history of who the current owner is as well as when it first minted or transferred to another user.



Learning Checklist
  • NFTs are unique assets owned by a specific address
  • NFTs are not unexchangeable and cannot be divided into smaller units to form the same value
  • Each NFT contains distinguishable information like the owner of the digital asset, who it was sold to etc.
  • All records of transactions are stored on the blockchain
Step 2: Introduction to Decentralized Storage
When an NFT is minted onto the blockchain, only the metadata of the NFT is stored on the blockchain. Metadata refers to a set of data that describes information about an item, like name of author, date of creation etc. The actual image itself for an image NFT is usually stored off-chain in a decentralized storage hosting site. In most cases, the NFT smart contracts usually contain the off-chain location of where the image is stored. The reason why storing images on-chain is not often done is because images require a lot of storage space, and in the blockchain world, storage space is expensive!
The most common decentralized storage solution used to store NFT data is Interplanetary File System (IPFS). IPFS is a distributed peer-to-peer network on which files are stored across multiple nodes, making them resistant to single points of failure such as server issues unlike centralized storages like Amazon or Google where the chances of their servers shutting down is higher. 

Decentralized storage is mainly preferred due to the nature in which it serves information on the web. Currently the Internet works off a location-based addressing where users go to a URL and the URL points to servers in certain locations. However, for decentralized storage platforms like IPFS, you can choose where you get your content from and you can set your privacy of what peers/nodes you trust to receive your files.

Article: What is Decentralized Storage 

Learning Checklist
  • Decentralized storage is where data is stored on a decentralized network across multiple locations by users or groups who are incentivized to join, store, and keep data accessible
  • Retrieval of data from decentralized storage is handled by nearby peers regardless of physical location
  • Centralized storage systems often result in network bottlenecks if traffic is larger than the network can handle. Decentralized storage allows multiple copies to be stored on different nodes, therefore allowing more copies of the data which then leads to faster download speeds
  • With potentially many participating nodes in a decentralized storage network, extra copies of your data can be stored in case of transmission errors, lower results of file loss
Step 3: ERC721 Token Standard
Before going into creating an ERC721 smart contract, we need to first understand what is ERC721 token standard. ERC721 is essentially a token standard used for NFTs. All NFTs have a variable called the tokenId as well as a contract address. The ERC721 standard provides a lot of functionalities catered for NFTs. All ERC721 tokens are unique and can have different values than another token minted from the same smart sontract as each will have a unique tokenId.   
If a smart contract implements the following methods and events, it can be called an ERC721 NFT smart contract.
  • ownerOf: get the owner of a specific token
  • balanceOf: get the current token balance of an account
  • getApproved: approving an amount of token from an account can be moved by a third-party account
  • transferFrom: transferring tokens from one account to another

With these functions, users can transfer tokens from one account to another, to get the current token balance of an account, to get the owner of a specific token and also the total supply of the token available on the network. 

Article: What is ERC721? 

Learning Checklist
  • ERC721 is a token standard for Ethereum and Ethereum compatible virtual machine NFTs
  • The main characteristic of ERC721 tokens is that each one is unique. When an ERC721 token is created, there is one and only one of those tokens in existence
  • An ERC721 token is created by a smart contract programming language like Solidity that follow a template
  • NFTs offer the ability to tokenize anything that is unique and verify proof of ownership using blockchain technology

Step 7: Creating an ERC721 Token Smart Contract
Now, let's take a look at the ERC721 smart contract. Under the contracts directory, open up ButterflyToken.sol using a code editor of your choice.


The above code segment shows a contract named ButterflyToken. There are two variables declared - tokenCounter and MAX_TOKENS. 

Just to recap, variables in Solidity are defined and declared in this format: type visibility-modifiers variable-name. For example, uint256 public endTime, or the two variables in ButterflyToken. For MAX_TOKENS, we also give it a starting value of 1000.
 
The tokenCounter variable is used to keep track of the number of tokens minted. The MAX_TOKENS variable is the maximum supply of tokens that can be created. This is to make sure the number of tokens minted does not exceed the max supply which in this case is capped at 1000. 

Next, we will be writing the code in the mint function.

Firstly, we will use the require keyword to set conditions before the mint function can be called. The require keyword in Solidity allows the user to set a condition in order for the function to be called. 

require(tokenCounter < MAX_TOKENS, "ERC721: Max supply");

The code above makes sure that the number of tokens minted by the smart contract currently must be less than the maximum supply of 1000 before it can proceed. Add the code into your mint function.
 
Next, we will be utilising 2 functions from the ERC721 library we imported in line 4. 

_safeMint(msg.sender, tokenCounter);  _setTokenURI(tokenCounter, _tokenUri);  tokenCounter = tokenCounter + 1;

We will be writing a _safeMint() function and a _setTokenURI() function. Add the code above into your mint function as well.

The _safeMint() function takes in msg.sender and tokenCounter as parameters. The variable msg.sender refers to the wallet address calling this mint function. 

When the _safeMint() function is called, it will mint a token and transfer it to the wallet address calling the mint function. The _setTokenURI() function takes in a tokenId and uri as arguments. The function is used to set a token metadata. The metadata of an NFT contains information such as its description, name, image url etc.

Your mint function is now complete. The completed mint function in ButterflyToken can be found in ‘Working code’.
Working code
function mint(string memory _tokenUri) public payable {     require(tokenCounter < MAX_TOKENS, "ERC721: Max supply");     _safeMint(msg.sender, tokenCounter);     _setTokenURI(tokenCounter, _tokenUri);     tokenCounter = tokenCounter + 1;   }
Step 8: Solidity Concepts - Value Types & Visibility Modifiers
While we’re on this topic, let’s cover some of the popular value types in Solidity!


Another concept we’ve covered over the course of this campaign is that of function visibility modifiers. Here’s a more detailed description of them:

  • external − External functions are meant to be called by other contracts. They cannot be used for internal calls. State variables cannot be marked as external
  • public − Public functions/variables can be used both externally and internally
  • internal − Internal functions/variables can only be used internally or by derived contracts
  • private − Private functions/variables can only be used internally and not by derived contracts
Step 9: Preparing for Deployment
The next step before deployment is to compile the smart contract. But even before that, we’ll need to make changes to our Hardhat configuration file. Open up the hardhat.config.ts file and replace “INSERT_YOUR_PRIVATE_KEY_HERE” in line 6 with your Core wallet Recovery phrase. This is because we’ll be using our own Core wallet to deploy the ERC721 smart contract.
Next, we’re ready to compile the smart contract. We can do so by running the command below in our terminal.

npx hardhat compile

Now that we’ve compiled the smart contract, we’re ready to deploy the contract. In the scripts folder, open up the deploy_butterfly_token.ts file. This script contains the code that will be used to deploy our smart contract. Let’s take a look at the code within this script, in particular, we’ll be looking at the main() function.

A contractFactory in ethers.js is, like the name suggests, a factory contract that is used to produce smart contracts. In this case ButterflyToken is an instance for our smart contract created from the ‘factory’. 

In the next line, calling the deploy() function on a contractFactory will start the deployment. A console message is then printed out along with the deployed smart contract address. Once the contract is successfully deployed, a message “ButterflyToken deployed to (address)” will be printed out on the console. 

Now that we understand that script that we’re using to help us deploy the smart contract, let’s go ahead with the actual deployment!
Step 10: Deploying the Smart Contract
One last thing to do before deploying our smart contract - since we’re deploying our smart contract to the Avalanche Fuji Testnet, we’ll need to make sure that our Core wallet is funded with Testnet tokens. Recall that all transactions on the blockchain require paying some gas fees.
You should be very familiar with using a faucet by now. If you require a recap, refer to our earlier quests when we requested for tokens from a faucet. Else, you can access the faucet here.

Troubleshooting: if you have already submitted a request to the faucet in the past 24 hours and intend to make another request, you’ll notice that you’ll be faced with a 24 hour cooldown. Please try to identify the wallet that contains the previously located testnet tokens and transfer your tokens from that wallet instead. 

However, if you have lost access to that wallet and are still facing the cooldown blocker, you can request for Fuji AVAX testnet tokens from Avalanche’s Developer Relations team in their Discord server’s developers-chat. Note that this should not be your first option - be prudent with your testnet tokens.

Now we can deploy the contract by running the deployment script. We can do so by running the following code in our terminal.

npx hardhat run scripts/deploy_butterfly_token.ts --network avalanche_fuji

If you’ve successfully deployed your smart contract, your terminal output should show the address of your deployed smart contract. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you require a reference. IMPORTANT: Please make a note of your contract address as you will require it in subsequent quests.
